1 Intro

In this document we analyse the link between a select set of Sepages protocol variables (with a special focus on batch) and the urinary levels of all phenols with > 80% samples > LOD.

The protocol variables under study are:

  • Batch
  • Defreeze time
  • Transport time

As a reminder, the life cycle of a urine sample in sepages is:

Sample process in sepages

Number of urine samples by trimester
period n
T1 477
T3 456

2 Batch

  • Batch 9 used as reference

3 Defreeze time and transport time

Impossible values such as negative or null times were set to NA:

  • N negative or null defreeze times: 10
  • N negative or null transport times: 9

Transport time was log transformed due to strong skewness.

And defreeze times were used as tertiles because of the outliers that were pulling the trends.

4 Censorship

Data below LOD will be imputed by LOD/sqrt(2), OK when few number of samples < LOD.

6.1 DAG

DAG for variables in link with protocol variables.

6.2 Method

A multiple linear regression is fit between compound level and the three protocol variables of interest and further adjusted on known confounding factors (cf. DAG + phenols paper):

  • specific_gravity
  • sample_date (linear time trend)
  • sample_season (categorical)
  • period (T1 vs T3)
  • mom_edu (categorical)
  • mom_age (continuous)
  • mom_bmi (continuous)
  • parity (continuous)

Note: need to add occupation for bisphenols + tobacco

Corrections are then applied to all protocol variables with p < 0.2 using the betas from this model following the procedure described in (Mortamais et al. 2012). A second correction will also take into account specific gravity.
